Within the limits of the system, Audi active lane assist helps
you to stay in the lane with corrective steering input. You can
intervene at any time. The system is designed for highways and
developed roads.
See owner's manual.

Within the limits of the system, the distance warning measures
the time between you and the vehicle driving ahead at speeds
above approximately 65 km/h, and it warns you if the distance
is under the set warning threshold. See owners manual
Within the limits of the system, the distance warning indicates\nif the distance to the vehicle ahead is consistently less than one\nsecond. See owners manual

Within the limits of the system, adaptive cruise assist helps to
maintain the set distance to the vehicle ahead by braking and
accelerating. If necessary, it also uses steering input to help
you stay in the lane. The driver is always responsible for
operating the vehicle.
See owner's manual

Within the limits of the system and if the necessary
infrastructure is available, the traffic light information
recommends a speed at which to cross the next green traffic
light or informs you of the wait time at the next red light. See
owner's manual
Within the limits of the system, the exit warning alerts you of a\npotential collision with approaching traffic from the rear when\nopening a door. See owner's manual

Within the limits of the system, the emergency assist
warns you and slows down the vehicle to a stop
automatically when it detects driver inactivity.
See owner's manual

Within the limits of the system, the intersection assist informs
and warns you of critical traffic detected in front of the vehicle,
and may also warn you with a jerk if necessary. This is therefore
an assisting system. It is always the driver's responsibility to
correctly assess the traffic situation. See owner's manual.
Within the limits of the system, the hazard information\ninforms and warns you if you are approaching a hazardous\narea. See owner's manual

Within the limits of the system, the system gives a visual
and acoustic recommendation to take a break, if it detects
signs of inattentiveness.
See owner's manual
Night vision assist supports you when it is dark. It will detect\nand highlight pedestrians and large animals, and will warn you\nof them if necessary. See owner's manual

Within the limits of the system, the Audi pre sense functions
can initiate measures to protect the vehicle occupants and
other road users in certain hazardous situations. See owner's
manual
Within the limits of the system, the side assist warns you when\nchanging lanes in a critical situation. See owner's manual

Within the limits of the system, the Audi AI traffic pilot takes
over the vehicle guidance in traffic jams up to 60 km/h on
highways and similar roads. If the system is available, you can
activate it by pressing the Audi AI button and releasing the
pedals and steering wheel. The system is deactivated as soon
as you resume control of the vehicle.

Within the limits of the system, the speed warning helps you to
stay under a specific speed limit. The speed warning informs
you if you exceed a previously stored maximum speed. See
owner's manual

The speed warning helps you to stay under a specific maximum
speed. The system warns you if you exceed a previously stored
maximum speed. You can also specify a tolerance for the speed
requirement currently in effect, which you will also be warned
about. See owner's manual.

Within the limits of the system, the active lane departure
warning warns before driving over the lane markings. The
warning takes place visually and through the steering wheel
and optionally through a vibration of the steering wheel. You
can always intervene. The system is designed for the highway
and major roads.

Data memory for automated driving (DAF):
When the parking pilot is active, the relevant physical
measurements from the surrounding area monitoring system
are stored together with other vehicle data (see the data
packet section for a detailed description about this data) for
several seconds on a volatile circular buffer in the vehicle.
When the traffic jam pilot is active, the results from the
technical analysis of the driver availability recognition are
stored with the surrounding area monitoring system data for
several seconds on the above-mentioned circular buffer in the
vehicle. The data stored in the circular buffer is continuously
overwritten after several seconds by the newest data. This data
is deleted when the ignition is switched off. The data will be
permanently stored only if one of the following triggers to
record data occurs:
- Airbag deployment
- Autonomous emergency braking
If a trigger to record data is detected (for example, if an airbag
deploys), the physical measurements, which were stored
several seconds prior to the event on the circular buffer that is
being constantly overwritten, are then transmitted to and
stored in a hard drive within the vehicle - referred to as the data
memory for automated driving (DAF) To permanently store this
data in the DAF, there are six memory locations designated for
the traffic jam pilot and six memory locations for the parking
pilot. One data packet can be stored per one memory location.
The respective data packet contains data pertaining to the
following categories:
- Driver interaction (for example, the driver presses the brake
pedal or turns the steering wheel)
- Status of the traffic jam pilot/parking pilot function (for
example, "traffic jam pilot was activated")
- Vehicle dynamics (for example, linear and lateral acceleration)
- Surrounding area (for example, sensor range) - when the
traffic jam pilot is active, however not for the parking pilot: the
readiness of the driver to resume control of the vehicle (for
example, "the anonymous camera input data
indicates that the driver was ready to assume control of the
vehicle"). Depending on the triggering event, the data packets
are stored at different memory locations in the DAF:
a.) Data packets for accidents that are detected when the
traffic jam pilot or parking pilot is active:
If an accident is detected (meaning an airbag deployed), the
data packet from the last several seconds before the accident
will be permanently stored in the DAF. These data packets
cannot be overwritten. The DAF has up to six memory locations
for such events.
b.) Data packets for other defined events when the traffic jam
pilot or parking pilot is active:
If another defined event occurs when the traffic jam pilot or
parking pilot is active (meaning autonomous emergency
braking occurred), the data packet is stored in one of the six
DAF memory locations and can be overwritten. The data
packets for such events can be overwritten if the six designated
memory locations are full and another accident or another
defined event triggers a new data recording. If this is the case,
the oldest data packet capable of being overwritten is always
overwritten. The data packets stored for detected accidents
(scenario a. above) cannot be overwritten. The data described
above is processed locally in the vehicle. This data is not
transmitted automatically (for example, through an air
interface) to AUDI AG or other third parties. Therefore, the data
is only stored in the vehicle. AUDI AG does not have access to
this data in the vehicle.

Driver availability recognition:
Depending on the equipment, this vehicle may be equipped
with a technical function to detect driver availability.
Driver availability recognition is
always active during vehicle operation and cannot be
deactivated by the vehicle passengers.
For example, if the driver momentarily nods off, this function is
used to ensure the driver is still ready to resume control of the
vehicle when the traffic jam pilot is active, if it is necessary.
Even in automated driving mode, the driver must always be
able to resume driving based on the traffic conditions.
If the driver still does not resume control of the vehicle despite
multiple system prompts, the vehicle will stop, the emergency
flashers will turn on and an emergency call (eCall) will be
made. The driver availability recognition uses an infrared
camera that is installed in the upper section of the instrument
panel. The camera focuses on the driver's head. It cannot focus
on other areas of the vehicle (for example, the front passenger
seat).
The camera images are not recorded or saved; they are rather
transmitted directly to the control module in the vehicle
responsible for processing. 
This control module analyzes the current camera image using
an image analysis software. This image analysis software
determines physical measurements for human facial features
(for example, the general position of the nose, ears, or eyes)
and determines information about the driver's attentiveness
based on these measurements (for example, based on the
position of the head or the direction of the eyes). The image
analysis software may detect if the driver is, for example,
unconscious or has fallen asleep, and will use this information
to assess if the driver is ready to resume control of the vehicle.
The physical measurements generated by the image analysis
software are collected anonymously and do not have a name
attached to any person, and these measurements are not
permitted to reconstruct the driver's face (therefore, only
abstract physical measurements are collected). To
reactivate the driver availability recognition as quickly as
possible after stopping the vehicle, the above-mentioned
physical measurements are stored in a small amount of
memory space in the responsible control module. As soon as
the memory capacity in this control module is reached, the old
physical measurements are overwritten by the newest
measurements.

Surrounding area monitoring system:
The functionality of the traffic jam pilot and parking pilot
requires the vehicle's driving path to be detected and
evaluated. For this purpose, cameras installed on the outside
of the vehicle detect objects within the vehicle's range of
motion (for example, lane marker lines and guardrails). The
live images from the cameras are transmitted to the
responsible control module. The camera images are not
recorded or saved; they are rather transmitted directly to the
control module in the vehicle responsible for processing. This
control module analyzes the current camera image using an
image analysis software. This image analysis software
determines anonymous physical measurements and
approximate distances to stationary objects (for example,
guardrails) or to moving objects (for example, vehicles driving
ahead). The control module evaluates these physical
measurements and makes it possible for the traffic jam pilot or
parking pilot to control the vehicle. The anonymous physical
measurements are stored for several seconds on a volatile
memory in the control module. These cannot be linked to the
identity of a person or a vehicle (for example, faces or license
plates).
